ming biological sciences, his negotiation between science and religion, and his interpretation of the implications of Darwinian thought. They also each proposed alternative ways of making sense of Nietzsche’s unique question concerning the meaning of biological evolution “for life.” At the heart of the discussion were debates about the relation of facts and values, the place of divine purpose in the understanding of nonhuman and human agency, the concept of life, and the question of whether the sciences could offer resources to satisfy the human urge to discover sources of value in biological processes. The Moral Meaning of Nature focuses on the historical background of these questions, exposing the complex ways in which they recur in contemporary philosophical debate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEvolution (Biology)xMoral and ethical aspects. 0aEvolution (Biology)xReligious aspects. 0aEvolution (Biology)-Moral and ethical aspects. 0aEvolution (Biology)-Religious aspects. 0aLife. 0aNietzsche, Friedrich Wilhelm,-1844-1900. 0aOverbeck, Franz,-1837-1905. 0aPhilosophy and sciencezGermanyxHistory. 0aPhilosophy and science-Germany-History. 0aPhilosophy, Germany19th century. 0aPhilosophy, Germany20th century. 0aPhilosophy, German-19th century. 0aPhilosophy, German-20th century. 0aRickert, Heinrich,-1863-1936. 0aSimmel, Georg,-1858-1918. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aCharles Darwin.  aFriedrich Nietzsche.  aconcept of life.  aevolutionary ethics.  aphilosophy of biology.  aphilosophy of religion.  areligion and science.  ateleology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106885800 cprintz978022653975140uhttps:/